    "body": "According to the error message the supplied account is too long. Ethereum addresses are 160 bits long. The RPC interface uses hex encoding which makes it expect 40 bytes. According to the error message you supplied 56 byte for the address.\n\nThe same parsing logic is used for lock/unlocking accounts as for retrieving the balance. So I don't expect there to be an issue.\n\nIn the examples you give is a difference that might explain this:\n\n```\nprint \"Unlock account: %s\" % server.personal_unlockAccount(myaddress,\"GEHEIM\", 60)\nprint server.eth_getBalance([myaddress, \"latest\"])\n```\n\nIn the case of getBalance you pass an array, in the case of the unlock 3 parameters. Is this intentional? I expect the getBalance call to look like: `server.eth_getBalance(myaddress, \"latest\")`.\n",
